review_blob: Thin light sessionable pale ale, no head at all. Appearance of bright clear apple juice some large sediment chunks although dont think this bottle conditioned. Subtle noble hop and bread aroma. Easy enough to drink but dont think Ill be lining up for another
Deep garnet red with thin beige head, pretty subdued aroma, roast malt and dried fruit
Big hop aroma up front, pine dominating, pours golden orange with thin white head. Lacing. Strong lasting bitterness, good though, caramel malt to pull it all together. An approachable monster
Big hops, pine dominant. big malt, caramel first, approachable American ipa. Thin off white head, hazy copper gold

Fantastic, red brown, hazy, minimal tan head, no lacing, great malt balance with toffee and biscuit, balanced perfectly, highly sessionable, low bitterness, strong malt character with great hop highlights. a very enjoyable end to a holiday in aus
Light body, little aroma, thin head, bready malt flavour, slight sulphur hint in the taste.
Citrus, floral aroma lasting robust bitterness. Great drop, bready malt character behind all the hops

Aroma malt dominated with clove and spice, moderate tan to off white head, dark garnet red. Taste malt driven caramel, clove and spice with choc, some alcohol character. Warm toasty goodness. Full body, moderate carb, well balanced.

Great aroma from the bottle, malty with citrus and subtle pine. Lasting thin off white head with lacing, brilliant orange with gold. Well balanced medium to full body. Clean finish. Fruity. Highly sessionable
beer_name: McCashin Family Stoke Recognition (Jim Pollitt) Double Pale Ale

review_blob: Biscuity malt aroma, colour is amber red more than brown, some lacing and thin but lasting off white head, caramel and honey dominate flavour, good carb level, medium body, ho hum

Caramel with citrus, pretty subdued aroma, bright, colour is closer to amber more than red, vigourous pour, head doesn?t last, no lacing, lacking head and body. Caramel and honey sweetness dominate the flavours, wife got peach.. lingering bitterness, not out of character or unpleasant though, light body, high carb. A oncer

Bottle, Subdued hop -citrus and sweet caramel malt, little head, dispersed quickly, bright golden hue with orange hints. Strong nz hop on palate, medium sweetness, strong inital bitterness not lasting too long, medium body, pleasant, sessionable
